{"type":"message","id":"d8196696","parentId":"93bb50be","timestamp":"2026-03-22T05:24:28.728Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_isyqxdmki526_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**Why:** Breakaway's memory reconstruction layer needs a focus decay mechanism. TemporalAttention provides:\n- Event store with time + focus-weighted retrieval\n- Topic-shift penalty (staleness increases when topic changes)\n- Already implemented, tested, and used in production\n\n**How:** Add TemporalAttention event store as the memory layer between sessions:\n- On pulse: write events to TemporalAttention store\n- On wake: query TemporalAttention instead of raw session logs\n- This gives Breakaway working memory without reinventing it\n\n**Location of TemporalAttention:** `C:/dev/temporal-attention/` (as `event_store/`)\n\n### Breakaway's Unique Bet\nSession gaps ARE the compression — not a bug to fix. No other architecture is working on this angle. Preserve it while borrowing what's proven.\n\n## Notes\n- Breakaway is stateless — each pulse is a fresh reconstruction\n- Gaps between sessions = compression, trust the files\n- Dual-head weight freezing (Infant) could inform causal layer weight management\n\n\n### Pending Actions\n# PENDING ACTIONS\nLast updated: 2026-03-21\n\n## Promises Made\n(None yet)\n\n## Deferred Tasks\n(None yet)\n\n[15 more lines in file. Use offset=160 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774157068726}}
