roup would only grab `(new` before hitting the space and closing paren. I should match everything on the old_text line including the parenthesized content, then capture the multi-line new_text block separately until I hit the file line.\n\n```\n\nActually, let me reconsider the format itself. The LLM outputs are in markdown code blocks with backticks, so the `old_text: (new file)` is just a single line, and `new_text:` starts a multi-line block that continues until the `file:` line. I need a pattern that captures the entire `new_text` content (which spans multiple lines) and then the `file:` line that follows it.\n\nThe issue with my current non-greedy `(.+?)` approach is that it stops too early. A greedy `.+` combined with a lookahead for the `file:` delimiter might work better to consume all the multi-line content between `new_text:` and `file:`. But wait—if the new_text itself could theoretically contain \"file:\", that becomes problematic. For now, I'll assume it won't, but I should double-check whether \"file:\" could actually appear in the markdown content itself.\n\nLooking at the actual content in `research/SIGNIFICANCE-SCORING.md`, I see things like `---` which wouldn't interfere with a \"file:\" search. The real issue is that the non-greedy quantifier stops at the first newline after `old_text:`, which breaks the pattern when the old text spans multiple lines or when there's whitespace involved.\n\nI should simplify this: just find the `### MUTATION` section and extract `file:` by looking for that line directly, then grab everything between `new_text:\\n` and that `file:` line as the actual replacement content.\n\nBut there's a bigger problem—during testing, the proposed mutation file never actually got saved to disk because the LLM call timed out. The regex never even had a chance to run. I need to fix the timeout issue first, then make the regex more robust for when the next mutation proposal comes through. Let me run the script again with the 60-second 