{"type":"message","id":"536b55c2","parentId":"9060c564","timestamp":"2026-03-22T05:33:01.904Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The LLM is outputting a MUTATION block with code fences (backticks), but my regex isn't handling the backticks properly. The format is:\n\n```\n### MUTATION\n```\nold_text: (new file)\nnew_text: ...\nfile: research/SIGNIFICANCE.md\n```\n```\n\nThe regex was:\n```\n'(?s)### MUTATION\\s*(?:```\\s*)?old_text:\\s*(.+?)\\s*\\nnew_text:\\s*\\n(.+?)\\s*\\nfile:\\s*(.+)'\n\n\n```\n\nBut the actual content starts with a newline after `### MUTATION` and then there's a code fence. The pattern is trying to match `old_text:` after optional backticks, but the non-greedy `(.+?)` is stopping too early when it encounters the newline, and it's not accounting for the fact that `new_text` comes after a newline following `old_text: (new file)`.\n\nLooking at the structure, after the closing backticks there's a `file:` line, but the `new_text` section itself spans multiple lines from its label to the closing backticks. I need to capture everything between `new_text:` and `file:` as the content, accounting for the fact that the backticks and newlines are just formatting around the actual data I need to extract.\n\n```\n(?s)### MUTATION\\s*```\\s*old_text:\\s*(.+?)\\s*\\nnew_text:\\s*\\n(.+?)\\s*\\nfile:\\s*(.+?)\\s*```\n```\n\nThis pattern with DOTALL mode should handle the multiline content in the new_text capture group, matching from the opening backticks through to the closing backticks after the file reference. The regex is still not matching correctly. The issue is that `(.+?)` followed by `\\s*\\n` will greedily consume trailing whitespace before the newline, so when trying to capture `(.+?)` it stops too early. For example, with `old_text: (new file) \\n`, the pattern matches `old_text: (new file)` because the non-greedy quantifier stops at the first opportunity to satisfy the rest of the pattern, even though there's technically whitespace before the newline.\n\nLet me reconsider with `old_text:\\s*(.+?)\\s*\\n`. The `\\s*` before the newline should be consuming that trailing space, so the captured group would only get `(new file)` without the space. I need to trace through what the regex is actually capturing versus what's being matched by the whitespace portion. I need to verify the regex pattern handles the actual format correctly. Looking at the LLM response structure, the backticks are on their own lines before and after the content, so `\\s*` should properly match that newline. For the `old_text` capture with `(new file)`, the non-greedy `(.+?)` will match minimally, stopping as soon as `\\s*\\n` can match the space and newline that follow.\n\nBut wait—the space after `(new file)` is actually matched by `\\s*` before `\\n`, not by the capture group itself. So the captured text is just `(new file)`. The real problem is that the capture group ends at the rightmost position where the overall pattern can still succeed, which means it's stopping too early when there's still more content to match.\n\nI should probably just adjust the pattern to be more lenient and test it directly against what the LLM is actually outputting. the newline and space after it get consumed by `\\s*\\n`. But the real problem is that `(.+?)` keeps matching more characters trying to satisfy the pattern, so when `\\s*\\n` appears at `)\\n`, it backtracks and captures the space too. For the file path, `(.+?)` followed by `\\s*\\n` means it only captures what's before the trailing space and newline.\n\nLooking at the actual format from the LLM response, the backticks are on their own lines, so I need to adjust the regex to handle this structure properly—matching `old_text: (new file)`, then the content between the backticks, and finally the file path.\n\nI'm working through a regex that captures these three parts with DOTALL mode enabled, so the `.+?` in the middle can match across newlines in the content section. Let me trace through whether this pattern will correctly extract `(.+?)` for the content and `(.+?)` for the file path when they're on separate lines with backticks. The regex might be failing due to how `.+?` interacts with `\\s*\\n` before `new_text:`. Let me trace through: if there's trailing whitespace or an unexpected character between `old_text:` and the newline, the pattern could break. I should add `\\s*` right after `old_text:` to handle any spacing issues. I'm also realizing the greedy `\\s*` before the newline will consume any trailing whitespace, which might be consuming the newline itself and causing the pattern to fail. I'm testing whether `(.+?)` with non-greedy matching handles the `(new file)` case correctly—it should capture the parenthetical text while `\\s*\\n` consumes the trailing space and newline. But I realize `\\s*` will match zero characters when there's no trailing space before the newline, so the pattern should still work. Let me just write and test the code to see if it actually matches. I think the real issue might be greedy matching of the outer `\\s*` before the newline, so let me test the updated regex directly.","thinkingSignature":"9704db4c4f1cd1e3124957e165fb9a811a9882267813e10b9a28554f580cf087"},{"type":"text","text":"The LLM is outputting a ` ``` ` code block for the mutation, but the regex wasn't handling the backtick block format. Let me fix the mutation parser:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_5b9kmfn2v7js_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1","oldText":"# Parse MUTATION block\n$mutationProposed = $false\nif ($llmResponse -match '(?s)### MUTATION\\s*(?:```\\s*)?old_text:\\s*(.+?)\\s*\\nnew_text:\\s*\\n(.+?)\\s*\\nfile:\\s*(.+)') {\n    $oldText = $matches[1].Trim()\n    $newText = $matches[2].Trim()\n    $file    = $matches[3].Trim()\n    if ($oldText -eq \"(new file)\") {\n        $mutationContent = \"$file`n---`n[NEW_FILE]`n---`n$newText\"\n    } else {\n 