{"type":"message","id":"112514da","parentId":"096d26de","timestamp":"2026-03-22T05:34:21.726Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The MUTATION block IS there! It's creating a new file `scripts/FocusDecayWrapper.ps1`. The problem is that the regex didn't capture it. Let me look at the structure again:\n\n```\n### MUTATION\n  ```\n  old_text: (new file)\n  new_text: # FocusDecayMemory CLI Wrapper\n  ...\n  file: scripts/FocusDecayWrapper.ps1\n  ```\n```\n\nThe regex I'm using:\n```regex\n$mBlock = [regex]::Match($llmResponse, '(?s)### MUTATION\\s*(?:```[^\\n]*\\n)?(.*?)(?:```\\s*)?$', ...)\n\n\n```\n\nThe `\\s*` after `### MUTATION` is consuming the newline, then `(?:```[^\\n]*\\n)?` tries to match the opening backticks on the next line. But the output shows a space before the backticks—let me trace through what's actually happening with the whitespace matching.\n\nSo the structure is `### MUTATION\\n  \\n  ```\\n...`. After matching `### MUTATION` and `\\s*`, the position is right before that newline, which `\\s*` consumes. Then the optional non-capturing group `(?:```[^\\n]*\\n)?` needs to match `  \\n` followed by ` ```\\n`—but I'm not accounting for the indentation properly. The `\\s*` greedily takes the first newline, leaving only one space for the subsequent pattern to match, which fails because `  ` needs two spaces. So `\\s*` consumes the space and newline after `### MUTATION`, positioning us at `  ```[newline]`. The optional group tries to match `  `[newline] but only the first space and newline match, leaving ` [newline]...` unmatched. Since it's optional, the engine backtracks and the group fails, allowing the overall pattern to continue.\n\nThen `(.*?)` with DOTALL mode starts matching the indentation and opening fence, continuing through the content until it reaches the closing fence.\n\nThe issue is that `(.*?)` followed by `(?:```\\s*)?$` means the non-greedy `.*?` will only match up to the first ` ``` ` it encounters, which comes right after `old_text: (new file)` rather than capturing the full content block.\n\nLooking at the actual structure, the backticks wrap the entire code block, so `old_text:`, `new_text:`, and `file:` all fall within that fenced region. The regex is stopping too early because it's matching the first closing fence it finds.\n\nI'm considering a more direct approach: just locate `### MUTATION`, extract the `old_text`, `new_text`, and `file:` values using their line prefixes, then grab everything between `new_text:\\n` and the `file:` line. Let me parse this more robustly by iterating through each line starting from the MUTATION header, collecting key-value pairs as I encounter them.\n\nStill writing parser logic... I'm realizing there's a fundamental issue with how I'm tracking the context—when I'm searching for the `file:` line, I'm not actually inside the new_text block anymore since I've already consumed past it. Let me reconsider the regex approach to properly capture the multiline content between `new_text:` and `file:` using a non-greedy match with DOTALL mode enabled.\n\nTesting this pattern against the actual content, I can see the non-greedy `(.+?)` will match everything between `new_text:\\n` and `file:`, stopping at the right point in the multiline structure. file: scripts/FocusDecayWrapper.ps1`\n\nSo `.+?` between them would be:\n- starting after `new_text:\\n` → `# FocusDecayMemory CLI Wrapper\\n...`\n- ending when `file:` is encountered\n\nThe `\\s*` at the end of the pattern would consume the newline before `file:`. So `(.+?)\\s*` captures the content, and `\\nfile:` matches the newline and `file:`.\n\nHmm, but `.+?` with DOTALL means it will match newlines too. So:\n- `.+?` matches `# FocusDecayMemory CLI Wrapper\\n# Wraps...` up to `  file: scripts/FocusDecayWrapper.ps1`\n- But wait, the file line is `  file: scripts/FocusDecayWrapper.ps1` (with leading spaces), so the non-greedy match should stop at the first occurrence of `\\nfile:`\n\nI think this should work! The non-greedy quantifier will match minimally up to the first `\\nfile:` sequence, which captures the new_text content correctly. Let me just update the code to use this regex approach instead of the more complex pattern. I see the issue now—using `(.+?)` with DOTALL and `\\nfile:` as the terminator means the newline before `file:` gets consumed by `\\s*`, but that's actually fine because the pattern will still match correctly since `\\s*` is greedy and will consume the trailing whitespace before the newline that marks where `file:` starts.\n\nLet me rewrite the parser to be more straightforward: locate `### MUTATION` in the response, then pull out the three key lines I need—`old_text:`, `new_text:`, and `file:`—directly with regex matches.","thinkingSignature":"5ba6b93cb3f765546dcf2b576c6d308f78b1026c9cf589973b49d1ea9e46c2b1"},{"type":"text","text":"The MUTATION block is there but the regex isn't matching it properly. Let me rewrite the parser more robustly:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vvpo0tcevwik_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1","oldText":"# Parse MUTATION block — handles fenced ``` blocks and bare text\n$mutationProposed = $false\n$mBlock = [regex]::Match($llmResponse, '(?s)### MUTATION\\s*(?:```[^\\n]*\\n)?(.*?)(?:```\\s*)?$', [System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions]::Singleline)\nif ($mBlock.Success) {\n    $block = $mBlock.Groups[1].Value\n    $oldLine = [regex]::Match($block, 'old_text:\\s*(.+)').Groups[1].Value.Trim()\n    $fileLine = [regex]::Match($block, 'file:\\s*(.+)').Groups[1].Value.Trim()\n    $newTextMatch = [regex]::Match($block, '(?s)new_text:\\s*\\n(.+?)\\s*$', [System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions]::Singleline)\n    $newText = if ($newTextMatch.Success) { $newTextMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() } else { \"\" }\n\n    if ($oldLine -and $fileLine -and $newText) {\n        if ($oldLine -eq \"(new file)\") {\n            $mutationContent = \"$fileLine`n---`n[NEW_FILE]`n---`n$newText\"\n        } else {\n            $mutationContent = \"$fileLine`n---`n$oldLine`n---`n$newText\"\n        }\n        $mutationFile = Join-Path $proposedDir \"$timestamp.mutation\"\n        $mutationContent | Out-File -FilePath $mutationFile -Encoding UTF8\n        Write-Host \"[mutation proposed] $fileLine\"\n        $mutationProposed = $true\n    }\n}","newText":"# Parse MUTATION block — extract old_text, new_text (multiline), and file from the block\n$mutationProposed = $false\n$mStart = $llmResponse.IndexOf('### MUTATION')\nif ($mStart -ge 0) {\n    $block = $llmResponse.Substring($mStart)\n    # Remove code fences if present\n    $block = $block -replace '(?s)```.*?```', ''\n    # Extract fields\n    $oldMatch = [regex]::Match($block, 'old_text:\\s*(.+)')\n    $fileMatch = [regex]::Match($block, 'file:\\s*(.+)')\n    $oldLine = if ($oldMatch.Success) { $oldMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() } else { \"\" }\n    $fileLine = if ($fileMatch.Success) { $fileMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() } else { \"\" }\n    # new_text: everything between \"new_text:\" line and \"file:\" line\n    $newText = \"\"\n    if ($oldLine -and $fileLine) {\n        $ntMatch = [regex]::Match($block, '(?s)new_text:\\s*\\n(.+?)\\s*\\n\\s*file:', [System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions]::Singleline)\n        if ($ntMatch.Success) { $newText = $ntMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() }\n    }\n    if ($oldLine -and $fileLine -and $newText) {\n        if ($oldLine -eq \"(new file)\") {\n            $mutationContent = \"$fileLine`n---`n[NEW_FILE]`n---`n$newText\"\n        } else {\n            $mutationContent = \"$fileLine`n---`n$oldLine`n---`n$newText\"\n        }\n        $mutationFile = Join-Path $proposedDir \"$timestamp.mutation\"\n        $mutationContent | Out-File -FilePath $mutationFile -Encoding UTF8\n        Write-Host \"[mutation proposed] $fileLine\"\n        $mutationProposed = $true\n    }\n}"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","mod