{"type":"message","id":"8e51f0bc","parentId":"8244c16f","timestamp":"2026-03-22T06:22:40.125Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, the Groups indexing might be wrong. Let me think:\n`'(?:Create|Edit|Update|New file)[:\\s]+(?:``([^``]+)``|([^\\s]+))'`\n\nThe outer group `(?:...)` is non-capturing.\nGroup 1: `(?:``([^``]+)``|([^\\s]+))` - this IS capturing.\n- Alternative 1: ``([^``]+)`` - captures content inside double backticks → Groups[1]\n- Alternative 2: `[^\\s]+` - captures non-whitespace → Groups[2]\n\nWait, actually:\n- Groups[0] = full match\n\n\n- Groups[1] = first capturing group ``([^``]+)`` (content inside backticks)  \n- Groups[2] = second capturing group `([^\\s]+)` (no-backtick path)\n\nBut the `Create|Edit|Update|New file` part is in a non-capturing group `(?:...)`, so it doesn't add a group. Let me verify: `$actionText = \"Create research/SIGNIFICANCE-SCORING.md defining...\"`. The regex would match \"Create \" followed by the path.\n\nIf the path is backtick-wrapped like `` `research/SIGNIFICANCE-SCORING.md` ``, then Groups[1] captures `research/SIGNIFICANCE-SCORING.md` and Groups[2] is empty. If it's not wrapped, like `research/SIGNIFICANCE-SCORING.md`, then Groups[1] is empty and Groups[2] captures it instead.\n\nSo I need to use Groups[1] if it has a value, otherwise fall back to Groups[2]. But I'm checking the right group index here.","thinkingSignature":"8e0829bdd580b7daa3575f9d31aaf0a3607b6ee9e218bd6e8c2bb51560b5a521"},{"type":"text","text":"Also update the LLM prompt to be stricter about the format:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_2qivr11ufokw_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1","oldText":"Reply with exactly this format at the end:\n\n### OBSERVATION\n[1-2 sentence observation]\n\n### ACTION\n[Describe the file edit, or \"no-op\" if nothing needs changing]\n\n### MUTATION\nIf ACTION is not no-op, provide:\n```\nold_text: [exact text to find