{"type":"message","id":"672a503d","parentId":"a6289ec9","timestamp":"2026-03-22T06:25:33.495Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The error is \"You cannot call a method on a null-valued expression\" on `$rawContent.GetType().Name`. This means `$choices[0].message.content` is null. So `$resp.choices` has items but `$resp.choices[0].message.content` is null.\n\nThis is strange - the choices exist but the content is null. Let me check what the actual response structure is by looking at what `$resp.choices[0]` contains. The MiniMax API might put content in a different field.\n\nLet me check: in the MiniMax API response, the `message` might have a different structure. Looking at the test output earlier:```json{\n  \"message\": {\n    \"role\": \"assistant\",\n    \"content\": \"Hello there, how are you?\",\n    \"name\": \"MiniMax AI\",\n    \"audio_content\": \"\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\nSo `content` should be a field in `message`. But maybe when the model outputs a thinking block, the structure is different? Or maybe `$resp.choices` is a different type of object. Actually, wait - I just realized. When I do `Invoke-RestMethod`, PowerShell deserializes JSON to PSCustomObject. The `choices` field is an array. But what if the choices are structured differently?\n\nLet me check the MiniMax API response more carefully. Actually, looking at the test output again - the content was in `$resp.choices[0].message.content`. But what if in some cases the response structure is nested differently, like if there's an `n` parameter or something causing the structure to be different?\n\nOr maybe the issue is that the `ConvertTo-Json -Depth 5` in the script is creating a JSON string that isn't being parsed correctly by the API, causing it to return an error response that still has choices but with null content. That would explain why `$resp.choices` has items but the message content is empty.\n\nLet me trace through what's happening with the JSON conversion -