{"type":"message","id":"fcac8f4d","parentId":"b75f241f","timestamp":"2026-03-22T06:28:56.387Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The error says `$choices` is null. But `$resp.choices` is accessed via `$choices = $resp.choices`. This means `$resp.choices` is null.\n\nAnd the debug output from the debug script shows that choices ARE returned when the same API call is made. So what's different?\n\nWait - looking at the debug output format. The error says `Line 142` and shows `$choices[0] | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 3` - but this is actually inside an expandable string `\"...\"`. The issue is that `$choices` inside the double-quoted string is being interpreted as an empty variable!\n\nSo:\n```powershell\nWrite-Host \"[DEBUG] No choices. Full resp: $($resp | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 3)\"\n\n\n```\n\nWhen `$choices` is null, the string still evaluates - but `$choices[0]` inside the expandable string throws an error because you can't index into null. That's the secondary error, but the real issue is that `$resp.choices` was null in the first place.\n\nSo why would the MiniMax API return a response without choices? Let me think...\n\nOh! I just realized something. The pulse script creates a JSON body using `ConvertTo-Json -Depth 5`, which might be creating an object structure that the API doesn't recognize, causing it to return an error response without choices.\n\nActually, I just spotted something critical - there's an extra comma after the messages array in the hashtable definition. That would create malformed JSON when converted. But wait, in PowerShell hashtables, trailing commas aren't allowed in hashtable literals, so that shouldn't even parse in the first place.\n\n```\n\npowershell\n$body = @{\n    model = $LLMModel\n    max_tokens = 1200\n    messages = @(@{role = \"user\"; content = $llmPrompt})\n}\n```\n\nThis looks correct - the hashtable is properly formatted with the messages array as a nested object.\n\nNow I'm wondering if the `$llmPrompt` variable itself might contain problematic characters when it's inserted into the JSON. If it has unescaped double quotes or special characters, that could break the JSON structure even though `ConvertTo-Json` should handle escaping automatically. Let me trace through what happens when the prompt gets substituted in. I'm checking the message structure format that gets passed to the API - the `role` and `content` fields should serialize correctly through `ConvertTo-Json`, so that shouldn't be the issue.\n\nBut now I'm wondering if the API itself is the problem - maybe there's a rate limit or the key needs refreshing? Though that doesn't quite explain why the response structure would be different. Let me step back and look at what's actually different between the debug script that works versus the pulse script that doesn't.\n\nI should check if `$llmPrompt` is somehow evaluating to `$null` when embedded in the here-string - that would definitely cause the API to fail silently and return no choices.","thinkingSignature":"c8e18ae419fe80f27e889855c68eb5ec1522a15b53e7546e6e0d9b20a2fc12ff"},{"type":"text","text":"Let me add a debug line to show the prompt before sending:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_zgi78col2jgi_1","name":"read","arguments":{"offset":95,"limit":30,"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":58919,"output":675,"cacheRead":12287,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":71881,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774160917272}}
{"type":"message","id":"89c6fe68","parentId":"fcac8f4d","timestamp":"2026-03-22T06:28:56.399Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_zgi78col2jgi_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You are Breakaway — stateless discontinuous agent. Each pulse is a fresh reconstruction.\nYour job: ONE concrete action that advances your goals. Be specific. Prefer file edits.\n\nGoals:\n$goals\n\nPending:\n$pending\n\nRecent: $recentPulseSummary\n\n$appliedInfo\n\nReply with exactly this format at the end. IMPORTANT: you MUST include the file: line in MUTATION — it is required.\n\n### OBSERVATION\n[1-2 sentence observation]\n\n### ACTION\n[Describe the file edit concisely]\n\n### MUTATION\n```\nold_text: [exact text to find — or \"(new file)\" if creating new file]\nnew_text: [replacement text — keep it concise, a few lines max]\nfile: [required — relative path from sandbox root, e.g. research/my-doc.md or state/goals.md]\n```\n\"@\n\n$llmResponse = \"\"\n\n[114 more lines in file. Use offset=125 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774160936395}}
{"type":"message","id":"b7a2033e","parentId":"89c6fe68","timestamp":"2026-03-22T06:29:08.276Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the problem! The `$appliedInfo` is inside the here-string, and `$appliedInfo` is set AFTER the here-string in the script. Wait, no - let me check the order:Actually looking at the read output, the here-string ends at `\"@` and then `$llmResponse = \"\"` comes next. So the here-string IS before the API call. But the issue is `$appliedInfo` is referenced INSIDE the here-string, and `$appliedInfo` is a separate variable.\n\nLet me look at the order of variables in the script:\n1. `$goals` - set before\n2. `$pending` - set before\n3. `$recentPulseSummary` - set before\n\n\n4. `$appliedInfo` - set before\n\nSo all the variables used in the here-string should be set. But the problem is that inside a double-quoted here-string `@\"...\"@`, PowerShell DOES expand variables. So if `$appliedInfo` contains special characters like `$` or backticks, they could be interpolated incorrectly.\n\nWait, let me reconsider - the here-string IS using double quotes `@\"...\"@`. So PowerShell WILL try to expand variables like `$goals`, `$pending`, `$recentPulseSummary`, `$appliedInfo`. These should all be set by the time the here-string is evaluated.\n\nBut `$llmPrompt` is defined AFTER the here-string, which means if the here-string is evaluated when it's created, the variables inside it should already exist. The real issue might be that `$appliedInfo` contains characters that are being misinterpreted during expansion, or there's something about the order of evaluation I'm missing.","thinkingSignature":"9733f762356fd89a15e991cd63e616413127bb85436bcc7e3d9c9bf0cb2f5424"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vd3ikeaz6fiw_1","name":"read","arguments":{"offset":75,"limit":20,"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":59805,"output":394,"cacheRead":12287,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":72486,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774160936402}}
{"type":"message","id":"f2f6493e","parentId":"b7a2033e","timestamp":"2026-03-22T06:29:08.284Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_vd3ikeaz6fiw_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"        Move-Item $mfile.FullName \"$appliedDir\\$( $mfile.Name)\" -Force\n        Write-Host \"[mutation applied] $file\"\n        $appliedMutations += $file\n    }\n}\n\n# Re-read files post-mutation\n$goals   = if (Test-Path $goalsFile) { Get-Content $goalsFile -Raw } else { \"\" }\n$pending = if (Test-Path $pendingFile) { Get-Content $pendingFile -Raw } else { \"\" }\n\n# LLM call\n$apiKey = $LLMApiKey\nif (-not $apiKey) {\n    $keyFile = \"$SandboxRoot\\.llm_key\"\n    if (Test-Path $keyFile) { $apiKey = Get-Content $keyFile -Raw }\n}\n\n$appliedInfo = if ($appliedMutations.Count -gt 0) { \"Just applied: $($appliedMutations -join ', ')\" } else { \"No mutations applied this cycle.\" }\n\n$llmPrompt = @\"\n\n[144 more lines in file. Use offset=95 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774160948280}}
